text: I'm going to go against the grain here and admit I'm really looking forward to seeing this one. I get why some people might be turned off, it's one that's going to actually involve thinking and exploring a deeper topic, so if you're looking for a quick, easy to watch action flick it's obviously not going to be for you. For me, I love this type of thing...Like Crash, Seven Pounds, Pursuit of Happiness, Instinct - I love films that stay with me long after I've watched them and Will Smith is great in these types of roles. I haven't enjoyed some of his most recent stuff as much as I usually do, but this looks like he's going to be back on form for me. So roll on December!

text: I'm excited for the movie, seems rather enthralling, I won't judge until I watch it. But I guarantee that a fair amount of people that are enlightened by the music within the Trailers have only recently been exposed to Thomas J. Bergersen's epic work. It's about time "Remember Me" gained the spotlight, my personal favorite, the only other place I've heard it put into action is in AMVs. But it's ironic since I've been utterly obsessed with this song in particular for years now, so hearing it being used like this made the nostalgia skyrocket. Illusions was an unforgettable album. Hopefully this use of it will assist in those songs getting more recognition, the kind they deserve.

text: Collateral Beauty (True Beauty)  There is collateral beauty everywhere, the beauty is in where you find it.  Rare is a time that you find yourself, fractured from some event.  Unable to regain, the peace you had before.  Everything in your life seemingly, getting harder to handle anymore.  But if you stop, just for one moment in time.  Everything you see is still okay, and you are truly fine.  All is not really lost, you just had to find your way back.  Unbeknownst to you, God was picking up the slack.  There was never, time to fear.  You should have known, God was always here.  ~ Serena A Hibbard

text: This is a beautiful movie.  Unfortunately, it is for a selective audience.  I can understand why most people will pan it, because this movie is directed mostly to those who have suffered a personal loss or a tragedy. If you have had a pretty comfortable unmarked life, you might not get the uplifting message at the end. DON'T WATCH THIS IF YOU WANT ENTERTAINMENT.   The screenwriter, Allan Loeb, wrote this movie as a Christmas fable, similar to the 1946 movie, "It's a Wonderful LIfe". Just like George Bailey's angel in "It's a Wonderful Life", Howard Inlet, the movie's main character is visited by visible manifestations of Death, Love, & Time.   The movie ends with the premise that even within tragedy, there can be beauty and hope at some undefined point. And that point is different for everybody. Watch this movie to inspire and encourage you to look at loss & tragedy with a new perspective.

text: If you don't understand the twist in the film they are not actually 'actors' they really are time,death,love. I'll explain: Will smith needed time, death and love to help him through his depression so he therefore can see the three 'actors'.  Wills friend who's daughter does not love him anymore needs the 'actor of love' (Amy)to help him get his daughter back therefore he can see the 'actors' also.  Wills other friend that is dying of a illness needs the 'actor' death to help him through his hard time so he can also see the 3 'actors'  Wills other friend also really wants to be a mom but believe she is to old to have one and has run out of time therefore she needs the 'actor' time to help her believe she can still be a mom. Therefore she can see the 'actors' aswell.  So nobody else could see love,death,time in the movie just the people who need them desperately such as will and his friends. We know this because at the end of the movie when will has came out of his depression and no longer need the help of love,time,death, he can see them all on a bridge when he is with his girlfriend but the girlfriend can not see them, will watches them disappear as he no longer needs there help.

text: "You have to keep breaking your heart until opens." - Rumi  I think the reason people dislike the movie so much is because they do not understand it. The idea is that there's a pure beauty in pain and having the opportunity to experience love. The awkwardness in the film represents the different levels and view points, reasoning, to love.   My ex told me that I didn't know what love was. I remember looking back on our good times and realizing all of the moments I had fallen in love with him. I felt really sad about our break up and then this movie came to mind and I remember thinking, "No, I know exactly what love is. You're not ready for my love.  I'm not going to let you take this (the memory of feeling love)  from me." At one point I started laughing while I was crying because it all made so much since. Though our relationship was over, I was so happy that I got to experience love, even if it was one sided, and I was thankful. it's like standing in the face of everything that's hurting you and saying thank you.

text: Personally, I loved this movie...though, I could've done without the twist  ending. (Without wanting to give away and spoilers) I am referring to who the hired actors, ended up being. It seemed like a cop-out, and/or a cheap way of catching people off guard. Despite the fact the movie would've been better, without that twist (in my opinion) I still felt this was a well done movie - with great actors - that had me tearing up through it, in its entirety.   That all being said... short of that one cheap twist - I can't understand why this movie received such negative reviews...  :/

text: I was truly shocked when I saw the terrible reviews and comments the movie received. I loved it; it was an amazing concept done so beautifully. And man, is Will Smith an amazing actor.
